onomy. In order to assist the construction equipment industry recover from the depression it is in, I urge Congress to quickly pursue the following legislative initiatives to create new construction industry jobs and revitalize the construction equipment industry. ï¿½ Invest in critical infrastructure by swiftly passing multi-year reauthorization bills that increase investment in the nation's highways, public transportation, bridges, sewers, drinking water systems, and airports. To pay for investment in the highway program, Congress should support a user fee increase, the fairest and most fiscally responsible way to pay for additional revenue. Many leading business groups support a user fee increase, including AED, AEM, AAA, the American Trucking Associations, the National Association of Manufacturers, and the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ï¿½ Ensure that credit is available to equipment distributors, manufacturers, purchasers, and to developers. The construction industry is facing an unprecedented credit crisis. Congress and the executive branch must work together to put programs in place to ensure that dealers and manufacturers have access to capital to run their companies, that customers can get credit to buy equipment, and that developers can access the money they need to undertake new construction projects. ï¿½ Extend and expand the home purchase tax credit. ï¿½ Extend the stimulus bill's capital investment incentives and create new tax credits to encourage "clean diesel" equipment purchases. ï¿½ Extend and expand net operating loss (NOL) carry back rules. Congress should allow 2009 losses to be carried back for five years and significantly raise the eligibility cap for companies to take advantage of NOL carry-back benefits. I urge you to strongly consider the aforementioned proposals. Thank you for your consideration. Sincerely, H.W. Marvin III 7043330786

