Thank you!  I wish you & your family a happy new year, too.

As for my big dream, maybe you can help me with it, since its something I've only run into since I've moved to North Carolina.

I built my house on a lot on Salem Chapel Road, 1/2 mile south of the Stokes County line, so its physically located in Forsyth County.  From the time I purchased the lot & my realtor mistakenly requested Stokes County Health Department to do the tests for the well, there has been confusion about who does what & what services I'm entitled to. For example:

1.   Forsyth County assessed my house. I pay them property tax on both my house & car.
    - When I called for garbage pick-up with Waste Management, they said they don't do pick-up at this end of the road.  Yet, I see their trucks travel it at least twice a day.
       (Because I had to contract with Rural Garbage Service,
        who doesn't do recycling, I spent an hour on the web
        researching who to call, etc.,  When I called the
        Forsyth County recycling center closest to me (in
        Kernersville) I was told they only service as far as
        Walkertown & was given another number to call.
        Well, 4 different numbers & calls later, I was
        referred back to the same guy who said it didn't
        matter that I paid taxes to Forsyth County, my
        zip code is Walnut Cove & thats Stokes County.)

2.  As an AARP volunteer advocate who worked to pass Health Care Reform, I met with the representatives of my district - based on my residence in Forsyth County, even though my mailing address is Walnut Cove in Stokes County.  Sen. Brunstetter had no problem understanding my position, but Rep. Falwell sent me a rather brusque note saying I had errouneously contacted him when
I should have contact the Rep. from Stokes County.  Neither Mr. Falwell, nor Sen. Brunstetter told me which law, ordinance . . . whatever the correct term might be, is the one that needs to be changed so things can be handled more effectively & efficiently.

Its my understanding the current law reads that a mailing address is determined by how close a new residence is to an existing PO.   

Here's the solution - just add these words:  IN THE SAME COUNTY AS THE RESIDENCE

This point of frustration has really been brought home to me  since I started work in the Winston-Salem Local Census Office.  Several people have called into our office to be scheduled to take the tests for employment opportunities whose physical, residence address is in one county, but who when asked for their zip code have given one that shows on the map for another county, so have been told to call the Local Census Office for that zip code.  This is not right!  The person physically lives, pays taxes, votes, etc. in one county, but will be enumerated in another county.  The latter county will get the benefit of that count with their taxes, representation, grants, etc.

Whether its to help NC residents like myself who have to spend hours, days, weeks, months "fighting City Hall" just to get what is rightfully ours via our paid taxes lower our blood pressure, or the right county to have its residents counted, I'm hoping someone in your office can look into this matter & get it resolved so we can all "do the right thing".

After all, you did say to dream big!

Thank you for your time.

Sincerely,

Cindy  ( Cyd )   Dunne

