Comment: Dear Bev Perdue: For many years, marijuana has been viewed in American society as a âbadâ drug because of its illegality. Many American citizens find this drug to be morally wrong. The idea of the legalization of this drug has caused a great number of heated debates in America. Many opponents of the legalization of marijuana state that this drug is âbadâ for you, will increase health hazards, and is a âgatewayâ drug. These concerns are very logical and reasonable, but are not accurate. Marijuana is indeed very beneficial to your health, can help treat medical diseases, and has been proven not to be a âgatewayâ drug. The legalization of marijuana will have many benefits not only for the state of North Carolina, but for the entire country. A myth that appears numerously when concerned with marijuana is the fact that it is more harmful than alcohol or tobacco. It is essential for Americans to understand that marijuana has been scientifically proven to be less harmful than alcohol or tobacco if used in moderation. Moderate smoking of marijuana appears to pose minimal damage to the lungs. In fact, there have been no reports of lung cancer related solely to marijuana. Also, none of the medical tests currently used to detect brain damage in humans have found harm from marijuana, even from long term high-dose use. Heavy marijuana smokers exhibit no obstruction to the lungâs small airway. That indicates that people will not develop emphysema from smoking marijuana. Note that lung cancer, emphysema, and all of the other conditions listed above can be caused by cigarette smoking. Aside from the conditions it does not cause, marijuana also has numerous medical benefits. Marijuana greatly helps medical conditions. Research has found that marijuana actually works to slow down tumor growth in the lungs, breasts, and brain considerably. It has helps cancer patients deal with the nausea, fatigue, and other numerous symptoms that come with chemotherapy treatment. Marijuana is a muscle relaxant, and has âantispasmodicâ qualities. These qualities have been proven to be a very effect treatment for seizures. The Scripps Institute, in 2006, proved that the THC found in marijuana works to prevent Alzheimerâs by blocking the deposits in the brain that cause the disease. Despite these benefits, many experts argue that marijuana is a âgatewayâ drug, that is, cause people to use harder drugs. This is another important concept that Americans must understand, and another myth that must be abolished. Marijuana has not been scientifically proven to be a âgatewayâ drug. This drug has been scientifically proven to not cause people to use harder drugs, such as heroin. In fact, studies have shown that most marijuana users never use any other illegal drug. The âgatewayâ theory presents as a casual explanation, but is indeed a statistic that changes over time as different drugs increase or decrease in prevalence. Marijuana, for these reasons and many more, should be legalized. Our government must inform its citizens of the facts, benefits, and costs of marijuana. Many will find that the benefits outweigh the costs of the decision to legalize this drug. As a result, North Carolinaâs government must work to reform the marijuana prohibition laws. Citizens in return, need to know the important information and rally for the reform. California has already taken that step for reform, and as a result, this option for the legalization of marijuana will be on their 2010 ballot. This North Carolina government must take the same step. The road for reform of the marijuana prohibition laws needs to keep traveling until this country reaches the goal of legalizing marijuana. Sincerely, Kayla Carmenia, David W. Butler High School

